Doc Del,<br><br>
As I read this post, I come upon a similar problem of understanding. I have lately gone back over this site to re-examine many of the more thorny issues, and I have noticed emerging several things that may explain the disconnect that you so eloquently describe.<br><br>
As Vietnam Veterans, we are the receptacle of a second &quot;culture&quot; created collectively by the soldiers in Vietnam. Like the culture or society from whence we came, and in which we find ourselves again, the NamVet &quot;culture&quot; had its own vocabulary and language, a mythology of sorts, rites of passage, and sets of personal and collective rules. Participation in this &quot;culture&quot; eased the task of survival and the pain of what the war was all about. In many ways, we are still part of that &quot;culture&quot; because we re-experience it in our interactions with one another and with people who were not involved.<br><br>
Vietnam Veterans can no more separate themselves from NamVet culture than Jews from Channukah, Muslims from Rammadan, Christians from Easter, The English from the Queen's birthday, Blacks from Martin Luther King Day, and  Americans from the Fourth of July, or &quot;D&quot; Day. <br><br>
The culture that served us so well in Vietnam remains at odds with many Americans who were not there. Being Americans as well, we are sometimes at odds with ourselves, too.<br><br>
This is the &quot;small Hindu shrine&quot; of the Vietnam Veteran.<br><br>
Having that perspective, and it is only my perspective, I am beginning to see that many of the problems being described on this post are the continuing, very human, and not very intellectually grounded expression of fears and prejudices that have plagued relationships since the beginning of time.<br><br>
That I see in myself two very different &quot;cultures&quot; and feel the conflict that the differences cause within myself and with relationships with others, gives me cause to be both cynical and opitmistic. Cynical in that I cannot change basic collective human nature, and optimistic that I can change myself.<br><br>
Doc, I am guessing this for myself, and I really don't know the &quot;why&quot; either, but if we can take a good long hard look into ourselves, then perhaps some of the problems you see and I see, too, may be resolved, at least on an individual and personal basis.   <br>
   
